        "authorId" : "d4c7fda6-9311-4eb9-91ca-d3f1cbccd288",
        "body" : "use `- include_tasks: \"{{ item }}\"` directly, no need to use `run-test.yml` (`- include_tasks: tests/basic.yml` works too)",
        "createdAt" : "2018-09-26T00:14:18Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2018-10-06T16:47:58Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "d4c7fda6-9311-4eb9-91ca-d3f1cbccd288",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "47601d9f-b129-4de6-b627-3bbc91c41a26",
        "parentId" : "481c21f7-9b74-47f7-abe4-c2f9ac0c440b",
        "authorId" : "d10c46ef-3d4c-4766-bd09-d27ec4674a84",
        "body" : "There's one big advantage over doing it this way: if you do all `include_tasks` directly, you will get the `included: .../tasks/tests/xxx.yml for localhost` all at the same time, while with this indirect include, you will get them before the tasks are actually executed. This makes it easier to find out in which file a task is defined (if you're hunting down something that breaks).",
        "createdAt" : "2018-09-26T03:36:02Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2018-10-06T16:47:58Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "d10c46ef-3d4c-4766-bd09-d27ec4674a84",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "d2264c75-f4d9-4e14-b70d-af7bc06033d9",
        "parentId" : "481c21f7-9b74-47f7-abe4-c2f9ac0c440b",
        "authorId" : "d10c46ef-3d4c-4766-bd09-d27ec4674a84",
        "body" : "(I originally did it directly for the docker_container tests, but after I had two tests instead of only one, I noticed this and changed it this way to make it easier to find out to which \"sub-test\" tests belong to.)",
        "createdAt" : "2018-09-26T03:36:52Z",
